If the institution of the week has any astronomieal significance, it is merely the natural one of an approximate quarter of the lunar mouth, like the Roman nundinae. Like the latter, the weeks among the Orientals got divorced from the natural and civil months, though the latter were never, except in Egypt and Rome, divorced from each other. The week was apparently a wide—spread institution, and its seven <lays were very early supposed to be connected with the seven planets; while the Sabbath was, so far as we know, exclusively Israelite.
